text.text:
In a city overrun with restaurants, cocktail bars and a pub on every corner, we sometimes forget about the humble cafe. But forget we shouldn't, as a good cafe is a truly wonderful thing - a malleable sort of place that sees to your needs whatever they may be.

Stop in for strong caffeine, or linger in a laptop-friendly nook; sit alone reading or gather friends over a hearty brunching; soothe your woes with tea or pep yourself up with a strong drink - whatever you do, do it at one of our favourites below.

tip.text:
Sandwiched between the hotter ends of Deptford and Peckham, New Cross can struggle to pull people in outside of the brooding Goldsmiths crowd. But The London Particular is doing more than its part to make the pilgrimage to SE14 worth while - this cafe-cum-restaurant is chilled during the day, vibey at night and quality throughout.

Come for great coffee, seasonal British fare and good conversation. Midday is our favourite time to visit - we canâ€™t resist their brunch bowls on a hazy Sunday afternoon, especially when the afternoon slowly slips into a boozy evening.

text.text:
Making the pilgrimage to New Cross worth while, this cafe-cum-restaurant is chilled during the day, vibey at night, and quality throughout. 

The spot is really made up of two next-door spaces: the cafe on the left, and the restaurant on the right. Both are open during the day, but the cafe shuts come nighttime when the party is ushered next door where the lights are dimmed and the wine is flowing. Come for great coffee, seasonal British fare and good conversation.

tip.text:
It might take a little while to find amidst Tottenhamâ€™s warehouse district, but once you reach Craving Coffee you'll discover all you need for a relaxing sip, bite or chill. The light pours in from their south-facing windows, illuminating soft woods, white tiles and, most importantly, delicious coffee and healthy bites from a kitchen where food is not just an afterthought.

Coffee was their starting point, but now theyâ€™re up to all sorts - lunch and dinner here feature carefully constructed European dishes with high quality ingredients. The food has certainly gone to their head with supper clubs sitting alongside a bill of exhibitions and other cultural happenings from the Tottenham community. Yes sir, it's a local favourite.

text.text:
It might take a little while to find, but once you reach Craving Coffee you'll find a relaxed spot worthy of a sip, a bite and a cotch. Think soft woods, white tiles, light pouring in from south-facing windows and, most importantly, delicious coffee and healthy bites from a kitchen where food is not just an afterthought. 

With an all-week alcohol licence, they've branched out into supper clubs, exhibitions and other cultural events too. Stop by to see why it's fast become a local favourite.

tip.text: We love this spot not just for the cheap coffee served in iconic tall glasses in little plastic cages; nor for the crisp natas with beautifully spiced custard that has only just set; nor for the shaded outside tables perfect for people watching. The real draw here is the palpable sense of energy in the room: older Portuguese women having a natter with their nata, the hiss of the coffee machine and the barks of the servers all becoming a rolling laid-back buzz that consumes and comforts you all at once. Itâ€™s very popular amongst locals, so you may have to wait for a seat - but once one becomes available feel free to plonk it down at any table outside and youâ€™ll be greeted with smiles and nods in true continental fashion.

text.text:
Locals know best, and most W10 natives will concur that despite its unglamorous appearance, Lisboa Patisserie is the place for a coffee and cake. Itâ€™s hard to miss the strong Portuguese influence on the Golborne road, so listen closely and follow the accents to this gem. 

Grab a table out front for the killer combination of coffee, custard tarts and people-watching - in true continental fashion.

tip.text: This buzzy coffee shop serves up some of the best beans in the city. These guys are serious about their roast, and it shows - the worker bees of Clerkenwell flock to this airy, modern cafe for a primo caffeine fix, be it filter or espresso-based. They swap their beans daily, and also offer some choice pastries alongside classic brekkie items like avo toast. You may even spot one of the #BabesOfDojo getting their pre-work cawf cawf at this spot.

text.text:
The worker bees of Clerkenwell flock to this airy, modern cafe for a primo caffeine fix, roasted expertly with Square Mile beans. If you're feeling adventurous, you can try one of their guest roasters sourced from across Europe. 

A delightful selection of pastries and a small menu of breakfast items should stave off any rumbling guts. If you're feeling inspired, they also run a barista school out of their basement.

tip.text:
Hidden away under the arches of Stamford Works, this minimal cafe - dressed up with a snazzy coffee machine and verdant foliage - makes some serious brunch magic. All day Saturday and Sunday, you can find their punk staff buzzing around the small space, constructing towering, Antipodean-inspired dishes that put the rest of E8's many, many brunch offerings to shame.

On a nice day, patrons spill out onto their sizeable courtyard, grazing on sourdough piled with chilli eggs and sipping on their expertly-crafted coffee. Their menu is pared back during the week, but you'll still find a good selection of favourite brunch dishes, plus a few lunch specials.

text.text:
Hidden away under the arches of Stamford Works, this minimal cafe - dressed up with a snazzy coffee machine and ample foliage - makes some serious brunch magic. All day Saturday and Sunday, you can find their punk staff buzzing around the small space, constructing towering, Antipodean-inspired dishes that put the rest of Dalston's many, many brunch offerings to shame. 

And on a nice day, patrons spill out onto their sizeable courtyard, grazing on sourdough piled with chilli eggs and sipping on cups of heavenly joe.

tip.text:
Spend enough time in The Hornbeam and you might just purge yourself of all the ailments of modern life - the place is solar powered for Christâ€™s sake. These good people are all about community, local produce, and keeping you green as a grasshopper. The seasonal menu (spelled out in fridge magnets) is primarily vegan and always tasty - come in the week for something simple like their pumpkin and kale tart, or on the weekend for their full English brekkie.

Food aside, the music is straight-up soulful and they even host classes. Pop in for a Jamming class (jam making) or a Jamminâ€™ class (guitar skills). Or both. Heck, weâ€™re community converts.

tip.text:
Haminados is just the kind of eccentric and cosy cafe that could become a favourite. The gregarious (potentially overly so) Greek owner Joseph has been here for nearly fifteen years running this place and he does it his way: a mixture of homemade deli-style grub and shit loads of memorabilia.

Mediterranean bites sit alongside bagels, sandwiches and salads in the kitchen, but on the walls is where the real action happens: a bizarrely captivating interior that resembles a joint fan-club HQ of the Beatles, Grease and Mamma Mia. Once you've taken it in, head out back to the little sun trap garden: an ideal place for sipping on a cappuccino with a slice of cherry pie.

tip.text: This charming cafÃ© is a bright little beacon on the rather grey main road in Denmark Hill. On a sunny day you'll spot young families and art students alike populating the colourful seating out front, brunching or lunching like they mean it. Upon entering you'll be met with a real feast for the eyes, with towers of homemade bakes and a legit fresh juice operation set amongst exposed brick walls, brightly coloured bunting and all manner of painted murals. It's a friendly sort of place that doesn't take itself too seriously, but continues to knock out wholesome and comforting food to the good folk of Camberwell â€“ think burgers, baguettes and a hearty veggie breakfast that has saved our skins on many an occasion.

It's a friendly sort of place that doesn't take itself too seriously, but continues to knock out wholesome and comforting brekkies, burgers, baguettes, baked goods and more.

tip.text:
Blink whilst walking past this itty-bitty cafÃ© and you might just miss it; clutching onto the front of a fully functioning upholstery workshop, Fowlds has been breathing life into the old â€˜good things, small packagesâ€™ thing since 2014. By day youâ€™re looking at all kinds of homemade pastries, cake and coffee, whilst the evening brings with it bar snacks, craft beer and zingy cocktails.

There may be somewhat of a table shortage inside but ample seating tumbles out onto the road, providing a great spot to park up and gaze at the original 1926 upholsterersâ€™ signage hanging out front. If youâ€™re lucky, you might even catch craft upholstery in action. Furniture restoration and coffee? Name a more iconic duo, weâ€™ll wait.

text.text:
Converted spaces seem to be all the rage these days, but Fowlds has one-upped this trend by creating a cafÃ© in the front space of a fully functioning upholstery workshop. Furniture restoration and coffee? Name a more iconic duo, weâ€™ll wait. 

Funded by the local residents of Addington Square, this community collab plays host to a daily changing menu of homemade salads, breakfast dishes and Square Mile coffee.

tip.text:
**Closed September 2018

Like its name would suggest, Rehab is an ideal break from the outside world. Everything is aligned to make you feel zen from the hanging plants to the food. The team are heavily into organic, homemade and vegan produce that's as locally sourced as possible. That may all sound a bit too worthy, but by George is it tasty.

Drinks contain the kind of superfoods and supplements you could spend hours reading up on and still not understand. MTC oil does what? We took their word for it and sipped on the delish' (and beautiful) Golden Milk - a blend of turmeric, ginger, black pepper, cinnamon, coconut oil, and maple syrup.

Food is just as thoughtful, and comes filled with exciting bits like house kimchi, nutritional yeast and homemade cashew cheese. It's fresh, colourful and creamy and doesn't leave you feeling like a rabbit. And those buckwheat banana pancakes, slathered in date caramel and raw vanilla ice cream? They'll be in our spank bank for weeks.

text.text:
Like its name would suggest, Rehab is an ideal break from the outside world. Everything is aligned to make you feel zen from the hanging plants to the food which is all organic, homemade and vegan.

Drinks contain the kind of superfoods and supplements you could spend hours reading up on and still not understand. But don't overthink it, just get stuck in to a rainbow bowl of flavours and health.

tip.text:
An Exmouth Market institution, Brill CafÃ© is the kind of homely, charming and assuredly indie cafÃ© weâ€™d write a song about were we in the songwriting business. Run by Jeremy Brill, who famously cycles to Brick Lane to get their bagels every morning, this place revolves around a particular holy trinity: music, bagels and coffee - which all, in their own way, bring a pure dose of pleasure.

The bagels are lightly toasted marvels, packed full of salmon, ham or cheese; their own-brew Coffee Officina blend tastes terrifically creamy with milk; and you can expect soulful, jazzy numbers all day long on vinyl which can also be bought along with a host of CDs. What makes this place stand out, though, is the sense of heartfelt bohemian community - plus a magical sun-trap garden that most of Exmouth doesnâ€™t know about.
